0," On a Train trip north toward Aberdeen, the Scottish poet and naturalist Kathleen Jamie witnessed an arresting optical illusion. As the rail car passed between the North Sea and winter woodlands, a reflection caused the nautical scene to mingle with the forest view from Ms. Jamieâ€™s window. â€œIf I narrowed my eyes,â€ she tells readers of â€œSurfacing,â€ her new collection of essays, â€œI could see both sea and trees at once. And now there was a ship! A ghostly tanker was sailing over the pine trees.â€ It was a lovely vision that another traveler, in the thrall of handheld technology, completely missed. â€œA woman nearby was on her mobile,â€ Ms. Jamie laments, â€œloud and getting louder. . . . Her fellow passengers were glancing at each other, rolling their eyes.â€ By Kathleen Jamie
