* BIG DAY AT THE SUPREME COURT: Today the Court hears arguments in the high-takes lawsuit by Texas and two dozen states against Obamaâ€™s executive actions on deportations. But law professor Erwin Chemerinsky predicts the challenge may go down on standing grounds:
The only harm claimed by Texas is the cost of its processing driversâ€™ licenses for those who are remaining in the country. Yet nothing in federal law requires that any state government lose money in the issuance of driversâ€™ licenses. It is an entirely self-imposed â€œcostâ€ and thus not a harm of the sort that the court â€” and especially its conservative justices â€” allow as a basis for standing to sue in federal court. If that were enough, any state could concoct a way to interfere with federal policies any time it wanted to bring a lawsuit.
