Yellow-bellied sea snakes are typically black and yellow with a broad, paddle-like tail. They can grow to the length of a baseball bat and are potentially lethal. Their venom contains a potent neurotoxin that stops muscles from communicating with nerve cells, and a single bite can cause respiratory, heart or nerve failure, according to the University of Hawaiiâ€™s Waikiki Aquarium.
Luckily, these serpents donâ€™t usually pose too much of a threat to humans because they spend most of their times in the warm, tropical waters of the Pacific and Indian Oceans. They rarely swim close to shore and never come onto dry land voluntarily â€” their tapered bellies prevent them from slithering.
